<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="ch09-onward-with-r-studio" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Onward with R-Studio</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      As an open source program with an active user community, R enjoys constant innovation
      thanks to the dedicated developers who work on it. One useful innovation was the
      development of R-Studio, a beautiful frame to hold your copy of R. This chapter walks
      through the installation of R-Studio and introduces <q>packages,</q> the key to the
      extensibility of R.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-rstudio-ide">
    <title>R-Studio as an IDE</title>

    <p>
      Joseph J. Allaire is a serial entrepreneur, software engineer, and the originator of
      some remarkable software products. Starting in 2009, Allaire began working with a
      small team to develop an open source program that enhances the usability and power
      of R.
    </p>

    <p>
      R-Studio is an Integrated Development Environment, abbreviated as IDE. Every software
      engineer knows that if you want to get serious about building something out of code,
      you must use an IDE. If you think of R as a piece of canvas rolled up and laying on
      the floor, R-Studio is like an elegant picture frame. R hangs in the middle of
      R-Studio, and like any good picture frame, enhances our appreciation of what is inside
      it.
    </p>

    <p>
      If we really want to <q>do</q> data science, we can't sit around typing commands every
      day. First of all, it will become boring very fast. Second of all, whoever is paying
      us to be a data scientist will get suspicious when he or she notices that we are
      retyping some of the commands we typed yesterday. Third, and perhaps most important,
      it is way too easy to make a mistake&#x2014;to create what computer scientists refer
      to as a bug&#x2014;if you are doing every little task by hand. Using an IDE, we can
      build reusable pieces.
    </p>

    <p>
      The website for R-Studio is <url href="http://www.rstudio.org/">http://www.rstudio.org/</url>
      and you can inspect the information there at any time. Make sure that you have the
      latest version of R installed before you begin with the installation of R-Studio. If
      you reach a page where you are asked to choose between installing R-Studio server and
      installing R-Studio as a desktop application on your computer, choose the latter.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-writing-functions">
    <title>Writing Your First Function: MyMode()</title>

    <p>
      Once you have installed R-Studio, you can run it immediately. Use the File menu to
      click <q>New</q> and in the sub-menu for <q>New</q> click <q>R Script.</q> In the
      upper left <q>pane</q> (sub-window), type the following to create your first function
      in R:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch9-mymode-v1">
      <code>
MyMode &lt;- function(myVector)
{
  return(myVector)
}
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      A function is a bundle of R code that can be used over and over again without having
      to retype it. We have called our function <c>MyMode</c>. Recall that the basic setup
      of R does not have a statistical mode function in it. We're going to fix that problem
      by creating our own mode function. The mode is the most frequently occurring item in
      a vector of numbers.
    </p>

    <p>
      In the lower left-hand pane of R-Studio you will notice that we have a regular R
      console running. Select all of the code for <c>MyMode()</c> and click the Run button.
      Then test it with:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch9-tinydata">
      <code>
tinyData &lt;- c(1,2,1,2,3,3,3,4,5,4,5)
MyMode(tinyData)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      Now let's build the function up step by step. First, add the <c>unique()</c> function
      to get a list of unique values:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch9-mymode-v2">
      <code>
MyMode &lt;- function(myVector)
{
  uniqueValues &lt;- unique(myVector)
  return(uniqueValues)
}
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      Then add <c>tabulate()</c> to count occurrences, and <c>which.max()</c> to find the
      most frequent:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch9-mymode-v3">
      <code>
MyMode &lt;- function(myVector)
{
  uniqueValues &lt;- unique(myVector)
  uniqueCounts &lt;- tabulate(
    match(myVector, uniqueValues))
  return(uniqueValues[which.max(uniqueCounts)])
}
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      Note that instead of tabulating every possible value, we only tabulate those items
      where there is a <q>match</q> between the list of unique values and what is in
      <c>myVector</c>. This correctly handles gaps in the data (e.g., when no values exist
      for some integers between the minimum and maximum).
    </p>

    <p>
      Before we leave this activity, make sure to save your work. Click on the File menu
      and then on Save. You can call the file <c>MyMode</c>. Note that R adds the
      <q>R</q> extension to the filename so that it is saved as <c>MyMode.R</c>.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-packages">
    <title>Installing and Using Packages</title>

    <p>
      Maybe someone else has already solved the same problem. In fact, for the statistical
      mode, there is an existing package that does just about everything you could imagine
      doing with the mode. The package is called <c>modeest</c>, a not very good
      abbreviation for mode-estimator. To install this package look in the lower right-hand
      pane of R-Studio. Click on the <q>Packages</q> tab and then click <q>Install
      Packages.</q> Type <c>modeest</c> to find and install the package. Once installed,
      activate the package by clicking the check box next to it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's try out the <c>mfv()</c> function. This function returns the <q>most frequent
      value</q> in a vector:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch9-mfv">
      <code>
mfv(tinyData)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      This is one of the great things about an open source program: you can easily look
      under the hood to see how things work by typing the name of the function at the R
      command line. The <c>mfv()</c> function also correctly returns a list of multiple
      modes when one exists in the data:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch9-multiple-modes">
      <code>
multiData &lt;- c(1,5,7,7,9,9,10)
mfv(multiData)
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      To recap, this chapter provided a basic introduction to R-Studio, an integrated
      development environment (IDE) for R. From this point forward, we will use R-Studio,
      rather than plain old R, in order to save and be able to reuse our work. R-Studio
      makes it easy to manage <q>packages</q> in R, and packages are the key to R's
      extensibility.
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch09">
    <title>Chapter Challenge</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch09-challenge">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write and test a new function called <c>MySamplingDistribution()</c> that creates
          a sampling distribution of means from a numeric input vector. You will need to
          integrate your knowledge of creating new functions from this chapter with your
          knowledge of creating sampling distributions from the previous chapter in order to
          create a working function. Make sure to give careful thought about the parameters
          you will need to pass to your function and what kind of data object your function
          will return.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

